BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:City of the Muse
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260412T113000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260412T143000
UID:bm-4868220260412@shop.queenbooks.ca
DESCRIPTION:[Off-site]\nFox Theatre presents\nCity of the Muse\nby Kate Hi
 lton! A complimentary screening of\nDeath on the Nile\n(2022) to follow (w
 ith popcorn\, of course!).\nKate Hilton is a bestselling Canadian writer. 
 In addition to\nCity of the Muse\n\, her fiction includes\nThe Hole in the
  Middle\, Just Like Family\n\, and\nBetter Luck Next Time\n. She is also t
 he coauthor\, with Elizabeth Renzetti\, of the Quill and Packet mystery se
 ries:\nBury the Lead\, Widows and Orphans\,\nand the forthcoming\nPut It t
 o Bed\n. When not writing\, Kate works as a psychotherapist in private pra
 ctice\, with a focus on personal reinvention and life transitions. She liv
 es with her family in Toronto.
LOCATION:Fox Theatre
URL:https://shop.queenbooks.ca/events
X-SOURCE:Queen Books
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:My Greek Mom's Recipes
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260416T183000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260416T203000
UID:bm-4958420260416@shop.queenbooks.ca
DESCRIPTION:[In Store]\nJoin us for the launch of\nMy Greek Mom's Recipes\
 nby Gus Constantellis. Meet the author\, mingle\, and get your book signed
 !\nGus Constantellis\n(@constantlygus) is an internationally touring Greek
  American comedian who has gone viral on social media many times for his f
 unny observations about immigrant culture. He grew up in Brooklyn\, New Yo
 rk\, and decided to pursue stand-up after trying it for the first time at 
 a talent show at NYU. Gus’s career took off during the pandemic after im
 personating his Greek mother in a wig\, subsequently leading him to\na nat
 ional headlining tour in 2022. He was recently featured on Comedy Central 
 and performs in clubs all around New York City. And while he’s amassed a
 lmost half-a-million followers across all social media platforms\, Gus beg
 an his career writing for several children’s television shows\, such as\
 nThe Lion Guard\, Rugrats\, Princess Power\,\nand\nGabby’s Dollhouse.
LOCATION:914 Queen Street East
URL:https://shop.queenbooks.ca/events
X-SOURCE:Queen Books
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:STORYTIME: FLOOR IT! by Bex Tobin Fine
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260418T103000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260418T113000
UID:bm-4867920260418@shop.queenbooks.ca
DESCRIPTION:[In Store]\nBring you little ones for a storytime of\nFLOOR IT
 !\nby Bex Tobin Jones.\nBex Tobin Fine\nis a writer of two picture books:\
 nFloor It!\nand\nYou Are Home\n. She has also written for the PBS show\nLy
 la in the Loop.\nHer past careers include solo violinist\, playing with or
 chestras including the Toronto Symphony Orchestra\, and voice actor in num
 erous animated shows such as\nRolie Polie Olie\nand\nMiss Spider’s Sunny
  Patch Friends\n. After getting her master’s degree from the University 
 of Toronto\, she taught high school English\, social science\, and science
 s. She now spends her time writing and exploring the world near and far wi
 th her family.
LOCATION:914 Queen Street East
URL:https://shop.queenbooks.ca/events
X-SOURCE:Queen Books
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Becalming
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260422T183000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260422T203000
UID:bm-4868020260422@shop.queenbooks.ca
DESCRIPTION:[In Store]\nJoin us for the launch of\nBecalming\nby Aga Maks
 imowska. Meet the author\, mingle\, and get your book signed!\nAga Maksimo
 wska\nis a writer whose debut novel\nGiant\n\, about premature sexual deve
 lopment and the fall of Communism in Poland\, was shortlisted for the Toro
 nto Book Award. Her writing has appeared in\nPolish[ed]: Poland Rooted in 
 Canadian Fiction\, Brick\, the Globe and Mail\, and others. Becalming\nis 
 her second novel. She lives in Toronto.
LOCATION:914 Queen Street East
URL:https://shop.queenbooks.ca/events
X-SOURCE:Queen Books
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:The Chip Stand
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260430T183000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260430T203000
UID:bm-4868120260430@shop.queenbooks.ca
DESCRIPTION:[In Store]\nJoin us for the launch of\nThe Chip Stand\nby Chan
 tal Bennett and Joel Kimmel. Meet the authors\, mingle\, and get your book
  signed!\nChantal Bennett\nis an editorial illustrator who enjoys illustra
 ting portraits\, icons and other things that reflect her passion for histo
 ry\, fashion history and cute vintage things in general. She also has a so
 ft spot for fairytales and turn-of-the-century illustrations. She studied 
 illustration at Parsons the New School for Design in NYC. When not working
  she enjoys historical sewing\, plein air painting\, printing on an 1800-p
 ound letterpress and hanging out with her husband\, Joel Kimmel\, and thei
 r beagles\, Peanut and Pistache.\nJoel Kimmel\nis an illustrator who speci
 alizes in portraits\, maps\, athletes and travel postcard illustrations. H
 e is a graduate of Sheridan College's illustration program. His work has a
 ppeared in numerous publications\, including\nMaroon Magazine\, Maclean's\
 , Scientific American\, Time\nand the\nWall Street Journal\n. He shares a 
 studio with his wife\, illustrator Chantal Bennett.
LOCATION:914 Queen Street East
URL:https://shop.queenbooks.ca/events
X-SOURCE:Queen Books
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:In Crow's Field
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260511T183000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260511T203000
UID:bm-5071720260511@shop.queenbooks.ca
DESCRIPTION:[In Store]\nJoin us for the launch of\nIn Crow's Field\nby Jud
 ith Thompson. Meet the author\, mingle\, and get your book signed!\nJudith
  Thompson\nis an award-winning playwright\, director\, actor\, and a profe
 ssor of theatre studies at the University of Guelph. She has twice won the
  Governor General’s Award\, for the play\nWhite Biting Dog\n(1984) and t
 he collection of plays\nThe Other Side of the Dark\n(1989)\, and has been 
 recognized with many other awards including the Order of Canada\, the Walt
 er Carsen Performing Arts Award\, the Toronto Arts Award\, the Epilepsy On
 tario Award\, several Dora Mavor Moore Awards\, the Floyd S. Chalmers Awar
 d for the plays\nI Am Yours\n(1987) and\nLion in the Streets\n(1991)\, the
  Amnesty International Freedom of Expression Award\, the B’nai B’rith 
 Award\, and many others. Her plays have been produced in many countries an
 d translated into several languages. In 2008\, she was the first Canadian 
 to receive the Susan Smith Blackburn Prize. She has received honorary doct
 orates from Thorneloe University in Sudbury\, Ontario\, and Queen’s Univ
 ersity in Kingston\, Ontario. Born in Montréal\, she now lives in Toronto
 .\nIn Crow’s Field\nis her first novel.
LOCATION:914 Queen Street East
URL:https://shop.queenbooks.ca/events
X-SOURCE:Queen Books
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:An Evening of Poetry: Sue Sinclair\, Ronna Bloom\, Puneet Dutt
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260514T183000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260514T203000
UID:bm-5071820260514@shop.queenbooks.ca
DESCRIPTION:[In Store]\nJoin us as Sue Sinclair\, Ronna Bloom\, and Puneet
  Dutt discuss poetry with host Jim Johnstone.\nMeet the authors\, mingle\,
  and get your book signed!\nSue Sinclair (she/her)\ngrew up in Newfoundlan
 d on the ancestral homelands of the Beothuk. She is the author of six prev
 ious collections of poetry\, including most recently\nAlmost Beauty: New a
 nd Selected Poems\n(Goose Lane Editions\, 2022)\, winner of New Brunswick
 ’s Fiddlehead Poetry Book Prize.\nHeaven’s Thieves\n(Brick Books\, 201
 6) won the Pat Lowther Award for the best book of poetry by a Canadian wom
 an. Sue teaches creative writing at the University of New Brunswick on Wə
 lastəkwey territory\, land of the “beautiful and bountiful river.”\nR
 onna Bloom\nis a Toronto-based poet and educator and the author of seven b
 ooks of poetry. Her work has been broadcast on CBC\, recorded by the Canad
 ian National Institute for the Blind\, and translated into Bangla and Chin
 ese. Ronna is also someone who puts poetry to work in the world\; she has 
 led many initiatives to bring poetry into health care settings\, specifica
 lly developing the first Poet-in-Residence program at Mount Sinai Hospital
 /Sinai Health. Ronna's most recent book is\nA Possible Trust: The Poetry o
 f Ronna Bloom\n\, selected with an introduction by Phil Hall (Wilfrid Laur
 ier University Press\, September 2023). www.ronnabloom.com\nPuneet Dutt\nr
 eceived her MA in English from Ryerson University. She is the author of th
 e chapbook\nPTSD south beach\n(Grey Borders Books)\, which was a Finalist 
 for the 2016 Breitling Chapbook Prize (Phantom Books). Her work has been p
 ublished in a number of journals and in\nImaginarium 4: The Best Canadian 
 Speculative Writing\n. She was born in India and raised in New Jersey. She
  now resides in Toronto with her husband\, where she is an editorial board
  member at Canthius and a creative writing workshop facilitator with the T
 oronto Writers Collective. She can be found online at puneetdutt.com.\nJim
  Johnstone\nis a poet\, editor\, and critic. His most recent books include
  a poetry collection\,\nThe King of Terrors\n(Coach House Books)\, as well
  as a book on micropress:\nWrite\, Print\, Fold\, and Staple\n(Gaspereau P
 ress). Johnstone runs Anstruther Press with his wife\, Erica Smith\, and c
 urates the Anstruther Books imprint at Palimpsest Press\, where he publish
 ed\nThe Next Wave: An Anthology of 21st Century Canadian Poetry\nin 2018.
LOCATION:914 Queen Street East
URL:https://shop.queenbooks.ca/events
X-SOURCE:Queen Books
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Restaurant Kid
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260526T183000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260526T200000
UID:bm-5072020260526@shop.queenbooks.ca
DESCRIPTION:[Off-site]\nThe Toronto Public Library presents Rachel Phan at
  TPL's Yorkville Branch!\nRachel Phan\nis a Chinese Canadian author. A gra
 duate of Toronto Metropolitan University’s Master of Journalism program\
 , she and her work have been featured on CBC\, Huffpost\, the\nWall Street
  Journal\, the Washington Post\,\nthe\nToronto Star\,\nthe\nNational Post\
 , Chatelaine\,\nand\nMaclean’s\n. Her instant national bestselling book\
 ,\nRestaurant Kid: A Memoir of Family and Belonging\n(2025)\, was named on
 e of CBC Books’ Best Books of 2025 and longlisted for Canada Reads in 20
 26. She lives in Toronto\, ON.
LOCATION:22 Yorkville Ave\, TPL Yorkville Branch
URL:https://shop.queenbooks.ca/events
X-SOURCE:Queen Books
END:VEVENT
END:VCALENDAR
